WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.000
I think that it is not a secret for many of us.

00:06.000 --> 00:12.000
We can be satisfied with those who lead us, or not.

00:12.000 --> 00:17.000
We can be sure that we would lead better.

00:17.000 --> 00:29.000
But unfortunately, we are in a situation where it is difficult for us to choose a hierarchy of subordination.

00:29.000 --> 00:32.000
It already exists in the organization.

00:32.000 --> 00:37.000
And we, entering this organization, are forced to accept this hierarchy.

00:37.000 --> 00:39.000
However, it can be accepted in different ways.

00:39.000 --> 00:45.000
It can be accepted harshly, to do only this and not a step to the side.

00:45.000 --> 00:52.000
Or, as for the same hierarchy that exists in the organization, it gives us a certain corridor.

00:52.000 --> 00:59.000
And in this corridor of possibilities, we can choose what suits us and what does not.

00:59.000 --> 01:03.000
If we are not satisfied with the corridor of possibilities, then let's look for another company.

01:03.000 --> 01:15.000
But the bigger the corridor that the company gives us, the more a person understands that this company has an opportunity for his individual development.

01:15.000 --> 01:21.000
And accordingly, he will value his work in this company, because it gives him the opportunity to develop.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
And not only to exploit him to get certain results.

01:24.000 --> 01:29.000
And accordingly, he will be interested in increasing the output.

01:29.000 --> 01:33.000
The same applies to the bureaucratic organization of work.

01:33.000 --> 01:40.000
I think many of us have come across the fact that in order to get a visa on a document,

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
you have to wait until this visa passes the appropriate stage of approval.

01:45.000 --> 01:47.000
Time goes by, opportunities are lost.

01:47.000 --> 01:55.000
And very often any of us criticizes this non-turning liberal machine that exists in this organization,

01:55.000 --> 02:04.000
because of which we miss benefits, because of which we miss those or other prerogatives and dividends on the market, and so on.

02:04.000 --> 02:09.000
Unfortunately, here you have to choose a balance.

02:09.000 --> 02:13.000
Any organization is a structure, and structures are impossible without bureaucracy.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.000
But again, bureaucracy can be different.

02:16.000 --> 02:18.000
It can be tough, it can be flexible.

02:18.000 --> 02:24.000
And accordingly, depending on what kind of bureaucratic structure exists in the organization,

02:24.000 --> 02:33.000
there are certain opportunities for the existence and implementation of human factors within this organization.

02:33.000 --> 02:35.000
And accordingly, if the system...

02:35.000 --> 02:38.000
And the bureaucratic system is not a candidate, it is not a child's play.

02:38.000 --> 02:39.000
We all live in a state.

02:39.000 --> 02:43.000
Any society is a certain bureaucratic system.

02:43.000 --> 02:49.000
We have to obey it because we live in this society.

02:49.000 --> 02:55.000
But if we find a system that does not burden us very much,

02:55.000 --> 03:02.000
we will be more interested in staying in this organization, developing in this organization,

03:02.000 --> 03:08.000
simply because this organization gives us more opportunities for our development

03:08.000 --> 03:14.000
and provides less obstacles for our functioning.

03:14.000 --> 03:21.000
The next element of the doctrine of human relations, which was proposed by me,

03:21.000 --> 03:24.000
concerns management.

03:25.000 --> 03:32.000
The fact is that according to the classical model, there was a strict hierarchy.

03:32.000 --> 03:39.000
If I am the boss, you must do what I tell you, and I don't care if you like it or not.

03:39.000 --> 03:48.000
We drew attention to the fact that managers should still focus on satisfying the needs of people.

03:49.000 --> 03:55.000
Yes, the manager's final task is to achieve maximum productivity.

03:55.000 --> 04:02.000
But if I constantly demonstrate and emphasize this task,

04:02.000 --> 04:05.000
that I don't care about you as a person, I care about your work,

04:05.000 --> 04:09.000
and if you have something wrong, I will always find you a replacement,

04:09.000 --> 04:12.000
well, accordingly, there will be a relationship.

04:12.000 --> 04:15.000
I will not be interested in working in this company.

04:15.000 --> 04:19.000
I will naturally look for another company where there are some different relations.

04:19.000 --> 04:24.000
The same thing, that's what I was talking about.

04:24.000 --> 04:28.000
From the fact that you are the boss, that you have more experience,

04:28.000 --> 04:34.000
it is not necessary to take into account the needs of your employees.

04:34.000 --> 04:40.000
If in the classical model the main attention of the manager is focused on technical factors,

04:41.000 --> 04:45.000
such as the performance of the machine, the weight of the machine, the lighting of the machine,

04:45.000 --> 04:49.000
the number of parts in this machine, the number of blanks,

04:49.000 --> 04:53.000
then this factor should still be taken into account.

04:53.000 --> 04:59.000
What does an employee need to work effectively?

05:00.000 --> 05:09.000
Salary, vacation, additional food, longer breaks for rest.

05:09.000 --> 05:14.000
That is, any person has certain needs,

05:14.000 --> 05:17.000
a person can get tired, and he wants to satisfy these needs.

05:17.000 --> 05:21.000
We work to be able to satisfy the needs we have.

05:21.000 --> 05:26.000
If the manager will pay attention,

05:26.000 --> 05:30.000
including to the subjective needs of the person,

05:30.000 --> 05:37.000
then the employee who will stop feeling like a slave to the machine

05:37.000 --> 05:42.000
will be interested in thanking such a manager.

05:42.000 --> 05:46.000
This will be manifested in the increase in productivity,

05:46.000 --> 05:49.000
maximization of profits,

05:49.000 --> 05:52.000
in the end, he will have more interest in work,

05:52.000 --> 05:55.000
and therefore he will do less marriage.

05:55.000 --> 05:58.000
That is, it is necessary...

05:58.000 --> 06:01.000
Maillot's formula is very simple.

06:01.000 --> 06:07.000
The manager should not forget that he is in charge of people, not machines.

06:07.000 --> 06:11.000
Now this phrase is obvious, but in the days of Maillot,

06:11.000 --> 06:14.000
this was the time of the Great Depression, we will remember it,

06:14.000 --> 06:19.000
that is, the time of the global economic collapse,

06:19.000 --> 06:24.000
it was a fundamentally new idea and a fundamentally new approach.

06:24.000 --> 06:33.000
At the same time, Maillot paid attention to the impact of material stimulation.

06:33.000 --> 06:36.000
As we remember, in the classical model,

06:36.000 --> 06:39.000
material stimulation played a major role,

06:39.000 --> 06:45.000
but Maillot noticed that in this case,

06:46.000 --> 06:54.000
individual reward should be supported by group, collective reward.

06:54.000 --> 06:58.000
That is, if I work well,

06:58.000 --> 07:03.000
then, accordingly, the productivity of not only me,

07:03.000 --> 07:07.000
but also the productivity of the group in which I work increases,

07:07.000 --> 07:11.000
and, therefore, there should be a support for group behavior.

07:11.000 --> 07:15.000
Here again, the ratio of group and individual.

07:15.000 --> 07:22.000
At the same time, Maillot paid attention to non-material stimulation.

07:22.000 --> 07:27.000
We remember that as for Taylor, he just noticed that in addition to material stimulation,

07:27.000 --> 07:34.000
there is also a social aspect that plays an important role in human behavior.

07:34.000 --> 07:38.000
As for Maillot and his doctrine of human relations,

07:38.000 --> 07:48.000
he directly states that material or economic stimuli should be supported by social and psychological.

07:48.000 --> 07:57.000
It is Maillot who introduces such a term as a favorable moral climate of the collective,

07:57.000 --> 08:01.000
or a psychological climate in the collective that exists.

08:01.000 --> 08:08.000
It is it that emphasizes that the presence of this favorable psychological climate

08:08.000 --> 08:12.000
will significantly contribute to the growth of labor productivity.

08:12.000 --> 08:16.000
Remember those girls he experimented with,

08:16.000 --> 08:19.000
and whom he forced to work almost in the dark,

08:19.000 --> 08:25.000
and the productivity of the labor did not fall below the productivity of those girls who worked in normal conditions.

08:25.000 --> 08:31.000
In addition to the psychological climate, the satisfaction of labor was of great importance.

08:31.000 --> 08:36.000
Today we know all this from the theory of Herzberg and the theory of motivations,

08:36.000 --> 08:41.000
which exist and are used in modern management.

08:41.000 --> 08:46.000
But all this is based on the experiments conducted by Maillot,

08:46.000 --> 08:49.000
and which found their reflection in his doctrine of human relations.

08:50.000 --> 08:54.000
Moreover, Maillot drew attention to the fact that

08:54.000 --> 09:02.000
the productivity of labor depends on the style of management that exists in the company.

09:02.000 --> 09:07.000
And the authoritarian style of management will, of course,

09:07.000 --> 09:11.000
lead to a certain limit to the growth of labor productivity.

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
But this will be a phenomenon of working from under the stick.

09:13.000 --> 09:17.000
As soon as the worker feels that this stick has weakened,

09:17.000 --> 09:21.000
he will immediately try to get away from work.

09:21.000 --> 09:28.000
And Maillot has repeatedly proved this with his experiments.

09:28.000 --> 09:34.000
If there is another, more democratic style of management,

09:34.000 --> 09:40.000
when the worker understands, believes that something depends on his opinion,

09:40.000 --> 09:44.000
no matter how much it is in fact, the main thing is that the worker believes so.

09:44.000 --> 09:48.000
This is already a management function,

09:48.000 --> 09:54.000
which is discussed and analyzed in the management theory.

09:54.000 --> 09:59.000
Then the worker will be interested in the manifestation of initiative,

09:59.000 --> 10:05.000
will be interested in the fact that the results and actions that he performs

10:05.000 --> 10:08.000
will help to increase the productivity of labor,

10:08.000 --> 10:11.000
so that he gets a certificate, gets praise,

10:11.000 --> 10:16.000
so that he, no matter how it sounds, but Maillot, pays attention to this.

10:16.000 --> 10:17.000
Let's hang it on the board of honor.

10:17.000 --> 10:24.000
Maillot was one of those who proposed to hang photos of front-line workers.

10:24.000 --> 10:29.000
So the board of honor also rises to the experiments of Maillot.

10:29.000 --> 10:34.000
These are, in principle, the main ideas of the doctrine of human relations,

10:35.000 --> 10:41.000
the main ideas of the human factor that we proposed.

10:41.000 --> 10:50.000
The Khatun experiment and the whole sphere of discovery of patterns associated with it

10:50.000 --> 10:56.000
represented the second stage of the development of the theory of organizational behavior.

10:56.000 --> 10:59.000
These are the 20s and 40s.

11:00.000 --> 11:06.000
Accordingly, what concerns this doctrine of human relations,

11:06.000 --> 11:10.000
here attention was focused on the human as such.

11:10.000 --> 11:17.000
Don't just think that the following extreme happened here.

11:17.000 --> 11:21.000
That is, if before, in the classics, they were engaged only in objective production,

11:21.000 --> 11:24.000
now they spit on production and began to engage in human.

11:24.000 --> 11:25.000
Of course not.

11:26.000 --> 11:33.000
As for business, a good, healthy business never throws itself into the extreme.

11:33.000 --> 11:38.000
Naturally, if a person does not have enough means of production,

11:38.000 --> 11:43.000
does not have the necessary equipment, he will not be able to produce something.

11:43.000 --> 11:48.000
But the same machines can be made more convenient for work.

11:48.000 --> 11:51.000
For example, a person could not stand on it, bending over,

11:51.000 --> 11:55.000
but could be in a comfortable position with a normal degree of displacement.

11:55.000 --> 12:02.000
And accordingly, there was also a focus on the fact that,

12:02.000 --> 12:06.000
as we said in the same classics,

12:06.000 --> 12:09.000
the enterprise is the work of a group.

12:09.000 --> 12:17.000
And accordingly, everything that concerns machines, equipment,

12:18.000 --> 12:24.000
it should have been satisfactory for one or another brigade.

12:24.000 --> 12:29.000
The task was to find out which groups the labor collectives were divided into.

12:29.000 --> 12:32.000
Large groups, small groups, medium groups.

12:32.000 --> 12:37.000
Because now, in addition to these objective characteristics,

12:37.000 --> 12:43.000
a very important value has become given to informal relations.

12:43.000 --> 12:46.000
Informal relations that may not even concern work.

12:46.000 --> 12:49.000
It may be informal relations that after work,

12:49.000 --> 12:53.000
we will go together to engage in some cultural events.

12:53.000 --> 12:59.000
And accordingly, we are interested in doing the work faster,

12:59.000 --> 13:00.000
to do it more successfully.

13:00.000 --> 13:02.000
Because if we do it badly,

13:02.000 --> 13:05.000
a disassembly will begin, where some mistakes have been completed.

13:05.000 --> 13:08.000
Reprocessing may begin,

13:08.000 --> 13:14.000
we may be forced to fix a marriage,

13:14.000 --> 13:17.000
and so there will be less time for communication.

13:17.000 --> 13:25.000
Again, as for the second stage of the theory of organizational behavior,

13:25.000 --> 13:34.000
more attention was paid to the style of management of the race and the theory of motivation.

13:34.000 --> 13:37.000
Once we introduce a person into production,

13:37.000 --> 13:40.000
then a person, as a living being, has its own motives,

13:40.000 --> 13:42.000
its own desires, its own needs,

13:42.000 --> 13:44.000
and these desires must be satisfied.

13:44.000 --> 13:48.000
A person works, and this is obvious, not to make the owner rich.

13:48.000 --> 13:53.000
A person works to find his place in life,

13:53.000 --> 13:56.000
to achieve any results that he has.

13:56.000 --> 14:03.000
If work allows him to significantly satisfy his desires,

14:03.000 --> 14:06.000
his needs, then I will stick to this work.

14:06.000 --> 14:10.000
If my work only makes me drink juices,

14:10.000 --> 14:19.000
then I will look for another job that, let's say, will see a person in me.

14:19.000 --> 14:28.000
Again, this stage, the second stage of the theory of organization,

14:28.000 --> 14:33.000
was associated with the fact that the management system has changed.

14:33.000 --> 14:42.000
The idea of delegating powers has emerged.

14:42.000 --> 14:44.000
Let's recall the classic.

14:44.000 --> 14:49.000
In the classic, the manager clearly says what, when, where, what to do.

14:49.000 --> 14:55.000
Now, in the non-classical stage of the doctrine of human relations,

14:55.000 --> 15:00.000
more attention has been paid to delegating powers.

15:00.000 --> 15:04.000
Okay, I have a general picture.

15:04.000 --> 15:07.000
In this picture, you must do this and that.

15:07.000 --> 15:12.000
I am delegating powers to you on the issue of releasing the elements you need.

15:12.000 --> 15:14.000
I am taking the initiative.

15:14.000 --> 15:17.000
But at the end of the day, there should be a certain number of products.

15:17.000 --> 15:19.000
How will you get them?

15:19.000 --> 15:21.000
I will not control you.

15:21.000 --> 15:24.000
I will not stand behind you to check.

15:24.000 --> 15:27.000
But I will control the final result.

15:28.000 --> 15:34.000
Thus, a great deal of attention was paid to the satisfaction of the individual,

15:34.000 --> 15:38.000
to the formation of his social needs, social stability.

15:38.000 --> 15:45.000
And perhaps a very important achievement of this second stage

15:45.000 --> 15:52.000
was the emergence of non-material stimulation.

15:52.000 --> 15:56.000
At that time, the terms like

15:56.000 --> 15:58.000
interdependent management,

15:58.000 --> 16:00.000
humanization of labor,

16:00.000 --> 16:03.000
implementation of certain group decisions,

16:03.000 --> 16:06.000
education of the employees,

16:06.000 --> 16:09.000
what is now called training and development of the staff,

16:09.000 --> 16:11.000
evaluation of motivation,

16:11.000 --> 16:15.000
all this takes the lead in these Khatun experiments.

16:15.000 --> 16:19.000
In the first place, in one way or another,

16:19.000 --> 16:24.000
a person is promoted as a necessary element,

16:24.000 --> 16:29.000
a necessary link of the functioning of the organization.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.000
And organizational behavior

16:32.000 --> 16:37.000
now becomes not just a behavior of servicing machines,

16:37.000 --> 16:40.000
it becomes the behavior of living people,

16:41.000 --> 16:44.000
who in the process of industrial production

16:44.000 --> 16:47.000
interact with a particular technique.

16:47.000 --> 16:52.000
And then the method of optimization of work with the technique is considered.

16:52.000 --> 16:55.000
How to achieve less fatigue,

16:55.000 --> 16:58.000
how to make the right breaks, and so on.

16:58.000 --> 17:05.000
This whole situation is connected with the second stage of organizational behavior.

17:05.000 --> 17:08.000
The first stage of organizational behavior

17:08.000 --> 17:15.000
was actually the stage before the beginning of the Second World War.

17:23.000 --> 17:29.000
It should be said that the beginning of the Second World War,

17:29.000 --> 17:32.000
no matter how strange it may sound,

17:32.000 --> 17:35.000
was a significant impact on organizational research.

17:35.000 --> 17:41.000
And, of course, it was largely connected with military needs.

17:41.000 --> 17:43.000
What is war?

17:43.000 --> 17:46.000
War is always the mobilization of a large number of people.

17:46.000 --> 17:54.000
Mobilization implies that a large number of non-military people come,

17:54.000 --> 17:58.000
who need to be taught very quickly

17:58.000 --> 18:02.000
to use one or another military technique,

18:02.000 --> 18:07.000
to use one or another weapon,

18:07.000 --> 18:14.000
and, of course, to teach people to achieve victories,

18:14.000 --> 18:16.000
to kill them less.

18:16.000 --> 18:22.000
As for the Second World War,

18:22.000 --> 18:29.000
this task arose in millions of people.

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
And the task was very simple.

18:32.000 --> 18:38.000
People came who had little desire to fight.

18:38.000 --> 18:41.000
They have completely different professions.

18:41.000 --> 18:45.000
They have families, children, and in the end they all want to live.

18:45.000 --> 18:47.000
And, of course, this is the main motive

18:47.000 --> 18:58.000
that makes these people master the relevant specialties and military professions as quickly as possible.

18:58.000 --> 19:01.000
The problem was education.

19:01.000 --> 19:07.000
And as for the third stage of organizational behavior,

19:07.000 --> 19:12.000
it is connected with the problem of education.

19:13.000 --> 19:18.000
The military actions that followed the Second World War

19:18.000 --> 19:29.000
were precisely the need to train military non-professionals in military actions.

19:29.000 --> 19:34.000
It is now that the education structure is beginning to develop.

19:34.000 --> 19:38.000
And more and more time, more and more attention

19:38.000 --> 19:47.000
is being paid to what was previously called re-training.

19:47.000 --> 19:54.000
And this re-training had to be put in pretty tough frames.

19:54.000 --> 20:03.000
It is during this period that a large number of psychological professional tests are being formed,

20:03.000 --> 20:08.000
which now use the theory of organizational behavior with great pleasure.

20:08.000 --> 20:13.000
It was necessary to understand the psychological stability of people,

20:13.000 --> 20:19.000
their temperament, their character, their scrupulousness, their pedanticism,

20:19.000 --> 20:23.000
their ability to work in stressful situations.

20:23.000 --> 20:29.000
To do this, it was necessary to sort out a large number of newcomers who come to you.

20:29.000 --> 20:33.000
And depending on their psychological properties,

20:33.000 --> 20:35.000
depending on their personality characteristics,

20:35.000 --> 20:38.000
that's what we were talking about,

20:38.000 --> 20:41.000
to distribute them among the ranks of the troops,

20:41.000 --> 20:48.000
to determine their type of occupation in a very large structure of military interactions.

20:48.000 --> 20:53.000
In the first place, in this case, of course, psychology stood out.

20:53.000 --> 20:58.000
And a huge number of tests, which we use now,

20:58.000 --> 21:01.000
were created in the 1940s.

21:01.000 --> 21:10.000
Psychological skills tests, professional readiness tests,

21:10.000 --> 21:15.000
professional adaptability tests, various differential surveyors,

21:15.000 --> 21:17.000
they are created at that time.

21:18.000 --> 21:27.000
Organizational behavior researchers realized what a powerful tool they had in their hands.

21:27.000 --> 21:31.000
The war was over, and, as they say, thank God.

21:31.000 --> 21:36.000
But now there are a lot of developments,

21:36.000 --> 21:39.000
the development of scientific material,

21:39.000 --> 21:46.000
which can be used, including in peaceful life.

21:46.000 --> 21:51.000
Moreover, these tests were valid, they were justified,

21:51.000 --> 21:54.000
they were reliable, reproducible,

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
and the main thing is that these tests were conducted on a large number of people.

21:57.000 --> 22:02.000
That is, these tests were approved, were standardized,

22:02.000 --> 22:04.000
and now I can apply them.

22:04.000 --> 22:08.000
This period is characterized by the fact

22:08.000 --> 22:15.000
that psychology begins to penetrate very strongly into organizational behavior.

22:15.000 --> 22:19.000
Well, of course, from the point of view of logic, everything is fine here.

22:19.000 --> 22:26.000
Mayot introduces human relations into the classic model of Taylor.

22:26.000 --> 22:29.000
Moreover, his human...

22:29.000 --> 22:32.000
Mayot still went from a psychological point of view,

22:32.000 --> 22:36.000
but he was engaged in a more social psychology,

22:36.000 --> 22:39.000
and again, he gave general recommendations,

22:39.000 --> 22:41.000
that's what we listed.

22:41.000 --> 22:43.000
And now we need specifics.

22:43.000 --> 22:45.000
The times of peace have come.

22:45.000 --> 22:48.000
The period of the restoration of the industrial economy begins again.

22:48.000 --> 22:51.000
New equipment, new equipment appears.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
The product of double purpose appears.

22:54.000 --> 23:02.000
Many military apparatus and mechanisms begin to be used in peaceful life.

23:02.000 --> 23:09.000
And, accordingly, now you can already identify more specific competencies,

23:09.000 --> 23:12.000
more specific abilities of people who are needed.

23:12.000 --> 23:18.000
What qualities should the dispatcher of civil aviation have?

23:18.000 --> 23:23.000
What qualities should the dispatcher of numerical program management machines have,

23:23.000 --> 23:26.000
which also arise at about this time?

23:26.000 --> 23:34.000
What qualities should a person have in order to be able to work with a large amount of information?

23:34.000 --> 23:45.000
How to ensure and achieve that a person is able to concentrate and switch attention from one detail to another,

23:45.000 --> 23:49.000
from one aspect of the functioning of the machine to another?

23:49.000 --> 23:52.000
After all, the technique becomes more complicated, a computational technique arises,

23:52.000 --> 23:57.000
more and more complex equipment appears, where the price of error is already great.

23:57.000 --> 24:00.000
If the cost of the machine increases at once,

24:00.000 --> 24:03.000
then, accordingly, if it breaks, the price of error increases.

24:03.000 --> 24:06.000
At the same time, another problem arises.

24:06.000 --> 24:14.000
If before, it was quite easy to train a worker to work with a machine,

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
it did not take much time, the machines were simple,

24:17.000 --> 24:27.000
now the technique presents to people, to the service staff, more and more strict requirements.

24:27.000 --> 24:35.000
The demand for education increases, the demand for retraining of people increases.

24:35.000 --> 24:39.000
You could work on one machine, they had one requirement.

24:39.000 --> 24:42.000
Now the machines have been replaced, not you went to another job.

24:42.000 --> 24:48.000
Due to the fact that new equipment is beginning to appear faster and faster,

24:48.000 --> 24:52.000
the machines change every 3-5 years.

24:52.000 --> 24:56.000
Accordingly, if this machine comes to the same factory,

24:56.000 --> 25:00.000
then why do you need to fire a person who already worked on an old machine?

25:00.000 --> 25:03.000
The old machine exhausted itself, and you removed it from the factory.

25:03.000 --> 25:12.000
Now you need to train a new worker to work on the previous machines.

25:12.000 --> 25:16.000
How to achieve processes? How to optimize this process?

25:17.000 --> 25:29.000
As for the post-war period, this stage was significantly related to the problems of training and development of the staff,

25:29.000 --> 25:33.000
with the widespread implementation of testing of the staff,

25:33.000 --> 25:40.000
and the ability to switch people's needs to new tasks.

25:40.000 --> 25:43.000
The tasks are gradually beginning to change.

25:43.000 --> 25:46.000
Not yet very quickly, but they are beginning to change.

25:46.000 --> 25:55.000
Accordingly, the requirements that are presented to you as a worker at the factory are changing.

25:55.000 --> 26:04.000
At the same time, the problem of assessing the staff begins to form again.

26:04.000 --> 26:12.000
What is the role of the staff in the development of the factory?

26:12.000 --> 26:23.000
If we look at the development of the theory of organizational behavior in the post-war period,

26:23.000 --> 26:27.000
this stage continues even now.

26:27.000 --> 26:31.000
The main tasks were laid down back then.

26:31.000 --> 26:35.000
I repeat, this is training and development of the staff,

26:35.000 --> 26:38.000
assessment and motivation of the staff.

26:38.000 --> 26:43.000
The fact that now human resources are included in the management area.

26:43.000 --> 26:48.000
But the structure of the organization itself has changed.

26:48.000 --> 26:57.000
Indeed, let's summarize what is understood today under the organization.

26:57.000 --> 27:05.000
Because when we talk about organizational behavior, it naturally revolves around one or another organization.

27:06.000 --> 27:08.000
There are a lot of models.

27:08.000 --> 27:15.000
Again, let's not get into different nuances, this is a separate topic.

27:15.000 --> 27:21.000
But the main thing in an organization, looking at this slide,

27:21.000 --> 27:25.000
is that any organization naturally consists of specific people.

27:25.000 --> 27:30.000
These are the individuals who make up its core.

27:30.000 --> 27:38.000
Modern organizations are such that people do not work alone, they always work in groups.

27:38.000 --> 27:41.000
And each group is responsible for something of their own.

27:41.000 --> 27:45.000
There is a finance department, an accounting department,

27:45.000 --> 27:49.000
an agreement making department, an administrative department,

27:49.000 --> 27:51.000
an HR department, and so on.

27:51.000 --> 27:58.000
That is, there are specific functional groups that need to be done.

27:58.000 --> 28:05.000
Therefore, individuals are grouped into groups that solve one or another functional task.

28:05.000 --> 28:10.000
And from these functional groups, an organization is formed as such.

28:10.000 --> 28:16.000
Of course, groups and tasks of IT organizations are the same as those of production organizations.

28:16.000 --> 28:21.000
An organization that provides services has its own structure and tasks.

28:21.000 --> 28:26.000
But as for organizations, they also do not exist in a vacuum.

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
All organizations exist in a certain external environment, in a certain society.

28:30.000 --> 28:36.000
Other organizations, state institutions, controlling bodies, tax authorities, and so on.

28:36.000 --> 28:44.000
And, accordingly, all these four spheres, they concern any organization.

28:44.000 --> 28:48.000
Therefore, all people included in the organization,

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
are included in addition to the group that is in the organization,

28:51.000 --> 28:56.000
and as part of the organization, they are included in the external social structure.

28:56.000 --> 29:03.000
This is a very important element, because it makes no sense to argue and talk about an organization as such.

29:03.000 --> 29:05.000
There are no autonomous organizations,

29:05.000 --> 29:13.000
because all organizations are always in direct interaction and contact with other people.

29:13.000 --> 29:18.000
No organization can never produce everything it needs.

29:18.000 --> 29:22.000
After all, its production is the production for other organizations.

29:22.000 --> 29:25.000
Otherwise, it will simply lose the meaning of business.

29:25.000 --> 29:30.000
Why is this organization model important to us?

29:30.000 --> 29:36.000
It is important to us because it highlights four main elements that each organization has.

29:36.000 --> 29:43.000
And accordingly, organizational behavior, if it is interested in describing reality,

29:43.000 --> 29:50.000
if it is an abstract discipline, it should take into account the behavior of all these four elements.

29:50.000 --> 29:58.000
And, of course, if we consider the modern theory of organizational behavior,

29:58.000 --> 30:05.000
then it can be described in the following way, which we see on this slide.

30:05.000 --> 30:14.000
In each organization there is a certain hierarchy, which we have already discussed.

30:14.000 --> 30:20.000
Today, it has become customary to talk not so much about the hierarchy of subordination,

30:20.000 --> 30:22.000
but about the hierarchy of leadership.

30:22.000 --> 30:30.000
Every organization has some leading positions, leading representatives.

30:31.000 --> 30:36.000
Depending on how well you cope with your position,

30:36.000 --> 30:39.000
depending on what authority you use,

30:39.000 --> 30:45.000
there is an authority of either a position or a personality.

30:45.000 --> 30:51.000
The authority of the position is assigned to you by the boss, so everyone must obey you.

30:51.000 --> 30:54.000
Let's recall the classic, it's Taylor-Foyle.

30:54.000 --> 30:57.000
Regardless of your level of competence.

30:58.000 --> 31:03.000
And yet, at the current stage of the organization's development,

31:03.000 --> 31:09.000
this leadership is replaced by the leadership of a personality.

31:09.000 --> 31:16.000
Yes, indeed, a person is a leader, but he has certain personal qualities

31:16.000 --> 31:21.000
that allow you to really be a leader and use authority.

31:21.000 --> 31:26.000
If you use authority, then, accordingly, you give someone else's command.

31:26.000 --> 31:33.000
If an employee does not understand something, but he knows that you are competent in your field,

31:33.000 --> 31:38.000
then, of course, he will do as he is told in order to gain experience

31:38.000 --> 31:46.000
and then understand what the meaning was, what were the functions and tasks of the instruction he received.

31:47.000 --> 31:51.000
In the end, a leader keeps in front of him the whole picture,

31:51.000 --> 31:58.000
which a line leader or even a middle-level leader does not have.

31:58.000 --> 32:02.000
In this regard, leadership is closely related to learning.

32:02.000 --> 32:09.000
It is no wonder that we said that one of the very important aspects of organizational behavior in the post-war period,

32:09.000 --> 32:14.000
and in our time, is the organization of learning, development, assessment and motivation.

32:14.000 --> 32:23.000
If we are in a company, and if we came to this company not only to get a salary and then go somewhere,

32:23.000 --> 32:31.000
if we link our career growth, our career development with this company,

32:31.000 --> 32:37.000
we learn, we learn the necessary competencies, we learn the necessary relationships.

32:37.000 --> 32:49.000
After all, very often we learn something by observing people, interaction of people, interaction of leaders,

32:49.000 --> 32:56.000
we try to imitate them, we try to be like those leaders who we like,

32:56.000 --> 33:03.000
and, accordingly, adopt their behavior styles, styles of reaction, styles of solving problems,

33:04.000 --> 33:08.000
their communication, their perception, their level of interaction.

33:08.000 --> 33:14.000
In addition, as we said, any organization is a group of people,

33:14.000 --> 33:19.000
therefore, a group dynamics becomes very important.

33:19.000 --> 33:32.000
Very often my success in the organization depends on the relations I have with the employees I interact with.

33:32.000 --> 33:40.000
If I have good cooperative relations, then I can always count on being told what to do,

33:40.000 --> 33:46.000
I will be protected from possible mistakes that I can make, I will be helped.

33:46.000 --> 33:56.000
If there are relations of competition, and, accordingly, everyone strives to achieve results at the expense of another,

33:56.000 --> 34:02.000
then internal conflicts, internal conflicts, negative internal relations arise,

34:02.000 --> 34:07.000
which, of course, leads to what is called a terrarium of like-minded people.

34:07.000 --> 34:15.000
We have little desire to be in such an organization, and no matter how interesting this organization is,

34:15.000 --> 34:21.000
no matter how interesting it is, I work with living people.

34:21.000 --> 34:31.000
And if this psychological atmosphere is unbearable for me, I will still look for another organization, no matter how interesting it is.

34:31.000 --> 34:37.000
Again, when we talk about organizational behavior,

34:37.000 --> 34:46.000
it is important to understand what kind of attitudes people have when they join this organization,

34:46.000 --> 34:57.000
what kind of relations people build, what they want to achieve, what their goals are, what their motivation level is,

34:57.000 --> 35:03.000
how the motivation level is set, how the level of achievement is achieved, how the level of compulsion is achieved,

35:03.000 --> 35:08.000
whether there is ambition, how ambitious my behavior can be.

35:08.000 --> 35:13.000
If I come out with different initiatives, how will they evaluate me?

35:13.000 --> 35:19.000
Will these initiatives be accepted or rejected?

35:19.000 --> 35:28.000
Will I get encouragement, or, on the contrary, will I be considered a jump and I will be in a social vacuum?

35:28.000 --> 35:33.000
How is the decision-making in this organization carried out?

35:33.000 --> 35:39.000
As for the management style, does it depend on me?

35:39.000 --> 35:45.000
Either I received a clear order that is no longer subject to change, not subject to discussion,

35:45.000 --> 35:56.000
or I get a decision that I can discuss and make changes to.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
Again, it is psychology.

35:58.000 --> 36:01.000
Who is a good manager?

36:01.000 --> 36:06.000
It is the person in whose office you come in with your opinion, and you come out with the opinion of the manager.

36:06.000 --> 36:12.000
Moreover, you come out not because you were ordered, but because the manager really justified his position.

36:12.000 --> 36:18.000
This is a very important situation for decision-making, because it is a person's attitude that reigns in the organization.

36:19.000 --> 36:26.000
If you know that your initiative will be welcomed, that you will not be put on the spot,

36:26.000 --> 36:36.000
and, accordingly, some of your proposals will be accepted and it will be emphasized that you took part in it,

36:36.000 --> 36:44.000
then purely human qualities of such an organization, which exists with such an organization,

36:44.000 --> 36:51.000
will be more acceptable to you and you will be pleased to go to work, you will not be afraid to make a mistake,

36:51.000 --> 36:55.000
simply because only the one who does nothing makes mistakes.

36:55.000 --> 37:06.000
All decisions are made in a normal working environment, and decisions are justified, proven, and agreed upon.

37:07.000 --> 37:15.000
Any organization today, as in any human behavior, is always associated with stress.

37:15.000 --> 37:20.000
There are plans that need to be fulfilled, there are tasks that need to be solved,

37:20.000 --> 37:27.000
and 24 hours a day, and only 8 hours of working time, and we must, accordingly, have time to work,

37:27.000 --> 37:35.000
and, remember, we talked about this, work is no more than a third of life, we must still have time to live our own life.

37:35.000 --> 37:42.000
Therefore, organizational behavior is directly associated with stress.

37:42.000 --> 37:48.000
We make mistakes, we fail, we succeed, we fail.

37:48.000 --> 37:56.000
Nevertheless, no one takes away from me the responsibility to implement and perform certain functions.

37:57.000 --> 37:59.000
And a person is constantly in stress.

37:59.000 --> 38:09.000
In principle, a low level of stress is a perfectly normal situation associated with human activity.

38:09.000 --> 38:13.000
Stress is always what arises in the condition of a lack of information.

38:13.000 --> 38:17.000
When we work, we always have a certain lack of information.

38:17.000 --> 38:21.000
We do not know what order will come today.

38:21.000 --> 38:25.000
We do not know what assessment will be received by the actions we have taken.

38:25.000 --> 38:30.000
And in this regard, work is always stress.

38:30.000 --> 38:36.000
But this stress can keep us in tune and give us an opportunity for career growth, for further development,

38:36.000 --> 38:42.000
or it can be the stress that leads to our complete destabilization,

38:42.000 --> 38:47.000
to complete lack of understanding, inability to find your place in this work,

38:47.000 --> 38:49.000
leads to diseases, and so on.

38:50.000 --> 38:55.000
Accordingly, stress should be optimal.

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000
This is also very important from the point of view of organizational behavior.

38:58.000 --> 39:06.000
Where are those boundaries that lead to the optimal functioning of a person?

39:06.000 --> 39:10.000
Any organization is always a conflict.

39:10.000 --> 39:14.000
Each person has his own desires, has his own tasks.

39:14.000 --> 39:17.000
And everyone wants to fulfill certain tasks.

39:17.000 --> 39:21.000
At the same time, the number of resources we have is limited.

39:21.000 --> 39:25.000
In the end, we need to get to the boss's reception.

39:25.000 --> 39:31.000
The sooner we get to him, the sooner we can start to fulfill the task that is before us.

39:31.000 --> 39:35.000
Again, disputes may arise.

39:35.000 --> 39:37.000
Who will come to the first boss?

39:37.000 --> 39:40.000
Who took the turn?

39:40.000 --> 39:45.000
Who found one or another way to approach the boss?

39:46.000 --> 39:49.000
A conflict is a perfectly normal situation.

39:49.000 --> 39:58.000
Because a conflict always arises in the conditions of the limitation of the resources we have.

39:58.000 --> 40:01.000
Organization is always a limitation of resources.

40:01.000 --> 40:03.000
At least a resource of time.

40:03.000 --> 40:07.000
We can be overwhelmed with more and more tasks,

40:07.000 --> 40:10.000
and we do not have time to fulfill them.

40:10.000 --> 40:15.000
And we do not fulfill them because we do not want to, we do not know how to, we cannot,

40:15.000 --> 40:17.000
or because we simply did not have enough time.

40:17.000 --> 40:22.000
We try to decide when to do a task.

40:22.000 --> 40:29.000
And, of course, an unfulfilled task leads to a conflict with the person for whom we had to fulfill it.

40:29.000 --> 40:35.000
When we are in communication, when we are in an organization, when we are with people,

40:35.000 --> 40:37.000
the communication aspect is very important.

40:37.000 --> 40:39.000
How do we interact?

40:39.000 --> 40:44.000
How can we and how quickly can we get the information we need?

40:44.000 --> 40:47.000
Is it desirable to be given this information?

40:47.000 --> 40:56.000
Or do we consciously not get anything in order to say later that we did not fulfill a task

40:56.000 --> 40:59.000
that shows my incompetence?

40:59.000 --> 41:03.000
Again, it is pointless to highlight some aspect here.

41:03.000 --> 41:05.000
All these aspects are interconnected.

41:05.000 --> 41:07.000
They are all tied to each other.

41:07.000 --> 41:13.000
And, accordingly, the communication that exists in an organization

41:13.000 --> 41:18.000
is directly connected with the psychological climate that exists in it.

41:18.000 --> 41:21.000
Again, how are teams implemented?

41:21.000 --> 41:25.000
How is the delegation of powers carried out?

41:25.000 --> 41:28.000
Or is this delegation not carried out?

41:28.000 --> 41:31.000
How is the delegation of responsibility carried out?

41:31.000 --> 41:33.000
Do I only answer for my part,

41:33.000 --> 41:39.000
or am I responsible for the success of the implementation of the entire group in which I am?

41:39.000 --> 41:46.000
And how much responsibility will I bear for the non-fulfillment and non-fulfillment of certain functions?

41:46.000 --> 41:54.000
And, again, if we talked about the fact that any organization is immersed in the external environment,

41:54.000 --> 41:59.000
then the problem area of organizational behavior is the power and politics

41:59.000 --> 42:03.000
among which the organization is implemented.

42:03.000 --> 42:10.000
Indeed, if there is assistance in the development of small, medium, large businesses,

42:10.000 --> 42:12.000
this is one thing.

42:12.000 --> 42:17.000
If there is a counteraction, if one or another social opinion, social attitude

42:17.000 --> 42:23.000
negatively evaluates the work in business, work in business structures, this is another thing.

42:23.000 --> 42:27.000
We all live, as I have already said, among other people.

42:27.000 --> 42:31.000
And therefore, it is important for us not only those relationships, or not only that opinion,

42:31.000 --> 42:34.000
not only those assessments that I am given within the organization where I am,

42:34.000 --> 42:37.000
but also assessments of other people who are significant to me,

42:37.000 --> 42:49.000
assessments of relatives, assessments of people who use a particular authority for me.

42:49.000 --> 42:56.000
This is exactly the area that covers the external sphere of the organization's activities.

42:56.000 --> 43:03.000
Again, as we can see, the field of modern organizational behavior is quite broad and extensive,

43:03.000 --> 43:08.000
and it concerns all aspects of human organization's activities.

43:08.000 --> 43:18.000
Therefore, today we can say that a new paradigm of organizational behavior is being formed.

43:18.000 --> 43:20.000
Or rather, it has already been formed.

43:20.000 --> 43:27.000
If we had a classic paradigm of Taylor-Fayol, a paradigm of human relations,

43:27.000 --> 43:30.000
the paradigm of human relations of Myo,

43:30.000 --> 43:36.000
then today there is a new paradigm of organizational behavior,

43:36.000 --> 43:46.000
which takes into account all the changes that have taken place in organizations,

43:46.000 --> 43:49.000
in the social structure, in the world.

43:49.000 --> 43:58.000
As for these changes, it is worth noting that the modern organization

43:58.000 --> 44:03.000
gradually moves away from rigid hierarchical structures

44:03.000 --> 44:08.000
and gradually moves to network or matrix structures.

44:08.000 --> 44:14.000
When a working group is created to solve a particular task,

44:14.000 --> 44:23.000
or certain connections and interactions between different departments of the organization

44:23.000 --> 44:25.000
to solve a particular task,

44:25.000 --> 44:30.000
and this is a temporary group that is created to solve the task that is now being solved.

44:30.000 --> 44:34.000
After this task is solved, the group will disintegrate,

44:34.000 --> 44:37.000
and we will create a new group, and so on.

44:37.000 --> 44:39.000
This does not mean that we will lose our work.

44:39.000 --> 44:49.000
It just means that the pre-determination that existed in the 80s of the last century has now disappeared.

44:49.000 --> 44:55.000
Now, if we want to meet the standards that the market presents to us,

44:55.000 --> 45:00.000
we must be able to react quickly to certain external tasks.

45:01.000 --> 45:15.000
The next point is related to the fact that now the knowledge carriers are gaining more and more importance.

45:15.000 --> 45:21.000
If a person had studied something before and could work at this machine all his life,

45:21.000 --> 45:25.000
or had studied a little, but still performed the same types of activities,

45:25.000 --> 45:27.000
now the situation has changed.

45:27.000 --> 45:30.000
A modern workplace, a modern organization,

45:30.000 --> 45:33.000
determines more and more requirements for its employees.

45:33.000 --> 45:41.000
They must be able to respond to the changes that are presented,

45:41.000 --> 45:50.000
and, accordingly, be able to react to all new innovations.

45:50.000 --> 45:54.000
Today, on average, once every five years,

45:54.000 --> 45:57.000
it is necessary to increase the level of qualification.

45:57.000 --> 46:02.000
Today, more and more people are studying for the MBA.

46:02.000 --> 46:07.000
You yourself spend your time to acquire new knowledge

46:07.000 --> 46:14.000
that will allow you to be more successful in your management activities, in your business.

46:15.000 --> 46:20.000
The next important change that has taken place in modern organizations

46:20.000 --> 46:27.000
is that if before, the main thing was the vertical division of labor

46:27.000 --> 46:31.000
from the hierarchy of subordinates, the boss, subordinate, and so on,

46:31.000 --> 46:35.000
now the horizontal division of labor is becoming more and more important.

46:35.000 --> 46:43.000
These network structures, these models of the matrix organization

46:43.000 --> 46:46.000
that exist now, are provided by the horizontal division of labor.

46:46.000 --> 46:52.000
Those or other groups are more successful in solving one or another problem.

46:52.000 --> 46:58.000
Therefore, the time of other groups should be spent on solving other problems,

46:58.000 --> 47:04.000
which, in general, will contribute to the solution of the problems that are in front of the organization.

47:04.000 --> 47:09.000
And this does not mean that you are worse at something or that you are doing something.

47:09.000 --> 47:14.000
Or that group is more elite or it uses more authority and respect of the management.

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
No, it's just that to solve these problems,

47:17.000 --> 47:26.000
competencies of the races and informal relationships that exist in this group are more successful than in another.

47:26.000 --> 47:28.000
This does not mean that your group is worse.

47:28.000 --> 47:35.000
This means that other problems will arise that will be more successfully solved by your group.

47:35.000 --> 47:39.000
The horizontal division of labor is now becoming more and more important,

47:39.000 --> 47:45.000
which is due to the emergence of new forms of business, virtual business organizations, IT organizations.

47:45.000 --> 47:47.000
And we'll talk about it a little later.

47:47.000 --> 47:59.000
It should be noted that in modern organizations, as has already been said, the content itself changes.

48:00.000 --> 48:07.000
Now, in order to be a successful businessman, constant training is necessary.

48:07.000 --> 48:09.000
This feedback is necessary.

48:09.000 --> 48:12.000
The requirements for the organization are increasing.

48:12.000 --> 48:15.000
The approaches that are given are constantly changing.

48:15.000 --> 48:20.000
And if you want to move forward with time, if you want to be successful,

48:20.000 --> 48:24.000
if you don't want to give your competitors the opportunity to outrun you, you have to learn.

48:25.000 --> 48:30.000
Moreover, this training should not be considered as if I don't know something or I'm stupider than someone.

48:30.000 --> 48:33.000
Knowledge is produced very quickly now.

48:33.000 --> 48:38.000
Work constantly receives new content, new content.

48:38.000 --> 48:47.000
If before the new amount of knowledge was obtained somewhere in a century,

48:48.000 --> 48:53.000
now, every decade, the amount of knowledge increases almost double.

48:53.000 --> 49:01.000
Moreover, now there is a tendency to reduce this time by doubling the amount of knowledge.

49:01.000 --> 49:06.000
This became particularly noticeable at the end of the 20th century,

49:06.000 --> 49:09.000
just at the time when we are living now.

49:09.000 --> 49:15.000
Because now there is a geometric growth of all new knowledge.

49:15.000 --> 49:20.000
And therefore, all the knowledge that we received at the institute is correct,

49:20.000 --> 49:21.000
this is good knowledge.

49:21.000 --> 49:25.000
But this is the knowledge that we received 10, 15, 20 years ago.

49:25.000 --> 49:29.000
Today, new additions, new changes have occurred.

49:29.000 --> 49:32.000
Why do we come to the same MBA course?

49:32.000 --> 49:39.000
After all, in fact, we consider what Taylor, Fayol considered.

49:39.000 --> 49:44.000
But on the other hand, this is the necessary base that we should know in the first place

49:44.000 --> 49:48.000
in order to be able to perceive new changes later.

49:48.000 --> 49:54.000
After all, look, the very same theory of organizational behavior has changed in almost 100 years.

49:54.000 --> 49:59.000
And what Taylor worked with is not what we work with today.

49:59.000 --> 50:03.000
Although, on the other hand, in order to understand modern trends,

50:03.000 --> 50:06.000
modern needs, modern opportunities,

50:06.000 --> 50:13.000
we need to know the ideas of Taylor, Fayol, Mayer, Liesbegger.

50:13.000 --> 50:18.000
Simply because they are all in demand today.

50:18.000 --> 50:20.000
Just in different volumes.

50:20.000 --> 50:28.000
In addition, it should be noted that if before, in the first half of the 20th century,

50:28.000 --> 50:32.000
there was a great importance of physical labor,

50:32.000 --> 50:36.000
then at the end of the 20th century and in our time, in the 21st century,

50:36.000 --> 50:40.000
more and more intellectual activities are growing.

50:40.000 --> 50:52.000
Indeed, if now no more than 5% of the US agricultural population feeds almost the entire world,

